  <section class="section-gray">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <h2>Thermador Range Repair — FAQ</h2>

      <h3>Why won't my Thermador Star Burner ignite?</h3>
      <p>On Pro Grand and Pro Harmony ranges, the five-point Star Burner uses a dual-electrode ignition. When it clicks but won't light, nine times out of ten the spark electrode has shifted out of tolerance with the star-tip geometry, or boil-over has flooded the igniter well. Both are fixable in one visit. Our techs carry OEM spark modules and Star Burner igniters for models back to 2010.</p>

      <h3>What does an F3 or F34 error code mean?</h3>
      <p>F3/F34 points to the oven temperature sensor (RTD) — either failed, loose at the rear connector, or showing resistance outside spec. One of the cleaner diagnoses we run — the sensor is a bolt-in replacement from the rear with the range pulled 6 inches out.</p>

      <h3>My ExtraLow simmer cycles off on its own — is that normal?</h3>
      <p>No. ExtraLow uses a secondary low-BTU valve that holds flame as low as 100°F. When the valve develops sticking or calibration drift — usually year 7 or 8 — it cuts flame mid-simmer on long-cook dishes. Valve replacement is a cooktop-off job but routine for our Thermador techs.</p>

      <h3>How much does Thermador range repair cost in Los Angeles?</h3>
      <p>Most Thermador range repairs run $300 to $700 for Pro Harmony all-gas and $400 to $950 for Pro Grand dual-fuel. Star Burner igniters, ExtraLow valves, and RTD sensors sit at the lower end; convection motors, control boards, and steam oven modules sit at the upper. The $89 diagnostic is waived the moment you approve the repair.</p>

      <h3>Can you convert my Thermador range between natural gas and LP?</h3>
      <p>Yes. Our techs carry Thermador factory conversion kits — orifices, regulator, and ExtraLow orifices are all separate. Tell the dispatcher your current fuel and destination when you schedule. About 90 minutes on a Pro Grand 48-inch, 60 on a 36-inch.</p>

      <h3>Do you service the steam oven on Pro Grand dual-fuel 48-inch ranges?</h3>
      <p>We do. The 1.4 cu ft steam oven on the PRD48JDSGU and related Pro Grand models uses a separate steam generator and water line that runs behind the range — different fault pattern than the main convection cavity. We diagnose both cavities in one visit.</p>

      <h3>Is it worth repairing a 12-year-old Pro Grand or should I replace?</h3>
      <p>Usually worth repairing. A new Pro Grand 48-inch dual-fuel is $14,000 to $18,000 installed. If our quote comes in under $1,500 and the cabinet frame, gas manifold, and oven cavity are sound, you're buying another 8 to 10 years. We'll tell you straight if it's the other way.</p>
